Health Authorities say the second wave numbers are proving to be even higher than in June with deaths increasing sharply over the last four weeks. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - The Western Cape needs extra 500 beds and more staff to cope with the spike in COVID-19 infections. Western Cape Premier, Alan Winde says they are also contracting more frontline workers  and calling for more volunteers. The province's hospitals are already under severe pressure as the number of patients admitted with COVID-19 continues to surge. "Frontline staff have been at this for nine months, and our wave is higher than the first wave." "We need to find another 500 beds, and every bed has to have staff. Its hospital beds, so we've gone out for a call for more volunteers," Winde said.